Insight and Recommendations for baywheels¶

by Caspar Heidbrink¶

Berlin, 08/07/2019¶

Investigation Overview¶

  • Growth pattern and influence of the current challenges regarding the law suit with the Bay's Metropolitan Transportation Commission as well as the deployment of ebikes
  • Patterns of bike usage by different user types and opportunities to improve utilization
  • Need for actively managing localization of the bikes (for docks in San Francisco and East Bay)

Dataset Overview¶

  • Data on bike-sharing from baywheels by Lyft for San Francisco, East Bay and San Jose
  • Offer: bikes from docks/stations (also some dockless in San Jose)
  • 3.6 million recorded trips over the last two years/24 months (July 2017 to June 2019)
  • Each dataset comprises information about users (having a subscription, gender, age), time and duration of the trip and start and end location

Overall Growth Afflicted by Current Legel and Technical Issues¶

  • From July 2017 to June 2019 trips per month were more than quadrupling from 44.1 thousand to 191.8 thousand.
  • However, in May 2019 monthly trips were dropping by 24% from April's 239.1 to 182.2, which is even below January 2019's figure.
  • June 2019 has seen a slight bounce back, which was mainly driven by growth in non-subscriber trips.
  • Recently reported issues with burning ebikes as well as bad press coverage in relation to the law suit with City authorities may well be the cause for this development.

Non-Subscribers Improve Off-Peak-Utilization (And Income!)¶

  • In the course of a day trips are strongly peaking like other traffic from 8am to 9am and from 5pm to 6pm with an average 500-600 trips per hour.
  • In between with average trips per hour around 250 utilization of the bikes is much lower.
  • The strong peaks are mainly driven by subscribers who are probably inhabitants of the operating areas and use the bikes to ride to and from work, but are much rarely able to use the bikes during the day.
  • On the other hand, non-subscribers, who are probably visitors to the area show a much more stable usage pattern over the day to do their casual trips (around an average of 50 trips per hour from 8am to 8pm).
  • Therefore, attracting more non-subscribers would help improve overall utilization.
  • As a very-positive side-effect, of course, this would generate additional income (approx. 5 USD/trip) which would be available to fund the required marketing.

# Calculation of average income per non-subscriber trip
# based on current pricing and historical usage pattern

# Pricing is based on 15min time spans
pricing_time_edges = np.arange(0, data['Duration [min]'].max() + 15, 15)

# First 30min cost 2 USD, every additional quarter of an hour 3 USD 
prices = np.array([2 + 3 * max(i - 2, 0) for i in range(len(pricing_time_edges))])

# Sum income for all time spans
non_subscriber_income = 0
for i in range(len(prices) - 1):
    non_subscriber_income += data.loc[(data['User Type'] == 'Non-Subscribers') & 
                                      (data['Duration [min]'] >= pricing_time_edges[i]) & 
                                      (data['Duration [min]'] < pricing_time_edges[i + 1]), 
                                      'User Type'].count() * prices[i + 1]

# Average the income per non-subscriber trip
income_per_non_subscriber_trip = non_subscriber_income / data[(data['User Type'] == 'Non-Subscribers')]['User Type'].count()

print(income_per_non_subscriber_trip)

Allocation of Bikes Must Be Actively Managed¶

  • Most bikes are bound to docks where the trips start/end (dockless only in San Jose).
  • During the course of a day there may occur imbalances of trips starting/ending.
  • As a consequence some docks on average tend to being emptied or jammed.
  • This leads to the need of an active management of bike allocation.
  • As average daily net gain/loss for some docks can be rather large, active allocation has to be performed multiple times a day.

# Extract relevant data for the plot
data = trip_data[trip_data['Start Area'].isin(['San Francisco', 'East Bay']) &
                 trip_data['End Area'].isin(['San Francisco', 'East Bay'])].copy()

# Transform data for plot
start_data = data[['Start Location', 'Start Latitude', 'Start Longitude', 'Trips [Thous. #]']]
start_data = start_data.groupby('Start Location').agg({'Start Latitude': 'min',
                                                       'Start Longitude': 'min', 
                                                       'Trips [Thous. #]': 'sum'})
start_data['Trips [Thous. #]'] = start_data['Trips [Thous. #]'] / 365 * 1_000 
start_data.columns = ['Latitude', 'Longitude', 'Avg. Daily Trips Starting']

end_data = data[['End Location', 'End Latitude', 'End Longitude', 'Trips [Thous. #]']]
end_data = end_data.groupby('End Location').agg({'End Latitude': 'min',
                                                 'End Longitude': 'min', 
                                                 'Trips [Thous. #]': 'sum'})
end_data['Trips [Thous. #]'] = end_data['Trips [Thous. #]'] / 365 * 1_000 
end_data.columns = ['Latitude', 'Longitude', 'Avg. Daily Trips Ending']

data = pd.merge(left=start_data, 
                right=end_data,
                how='outer', 
                left_index=True, 
                right_index=True, 
                suffixes=[' Start', ' End']).fillna(0)

data['Latitude'] = np.maximum(data['Latitude Start'], data['Latitude End'])
data['Longitude'] = np.minimum(data['Longitude Start'], data['Longitude End'])
data['Avg. Net Traffic'] = data['Avg. Daily Trips Starting'] - data['Avg. Daily Trips Ending']
data['Net Gainer/Looser'] = 'Net Gainer'
data.loc[data['Avg. Net Traffic'] < 0, 'Net Gainer/Looser'] = 'Net Looser'
data['Avg. Net Traffic'] = data['Avg. Net Traffic'].abs()

data = data[['Latitude', 'Longitude', 'Avg. Net Traffic', 'Net Gainer/Looser']]

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(24, 16))
